UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;<video controls="true"><source src="https://goalvow.com/upskilling/pluginfile.php/2981/mod_label/intro/13_Inclusive%20Communication.mp4">https://goalvow.com/upskilling/pluginfile.php/2981/mod_label/intro/13_Inclusive%20Communication.mp4</video>&nbsp;<br></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-2-inclusive-communication-lesson-13-a-quick-guide-to-accessible-writing';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><b>Summary</b></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong><em>Note:&nbsp;</em>Determine organizational readiness before pursuing inclusive conversations.&nbsp;</strong>Is &nbsp;your organization truly ready to facilitate these conversations in a healthy, respectful, and safe way? If not, ask,<em>&nbsp;what are some steps that we could take right now?</em>&nbsp;And start there. Some organizations may be ready to fully dive into inclusive conversations, while others should start with baby steps. Choose the approach that works best for your employees.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Your co-worker may not even realize they’ve said something offensive.&nbsp;</strong>While it’s easy to jump to conclusions when someone’s said something hurtful, it can be helpful to ask questions to clarify their message and intention.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><ul><li><strong>Forgive your mistakes.&nbsp;</strong>It’s normal to feel down about our mistakes but remember: No one is perfect. So, forgive yourself the next time your good intentions fall short. With so much diversity in the world, disconnects are inevitable. Rather than stressing about what you did, forgive yourself so you can focus on what you’ll do next. Divert your attention to the person harmed, and you’ll find it much easier to apologize sincerely and learn from the experience.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Prioritize transparency.&nbsp;</strong>Issues can’t be addressed if no one is aware of them. If you want actionable feedback, prioritize transparency. Ask people what they need, and then do your best to address those needs.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Remember, you are not your mistakes.&nbsp;</strong>Apologizing demonstrates integrity, professionalism, and the potential for change. Admitting you were wrong does not mean that you’re a failure or a bad person.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><ul><li><strong>Make your agreements visible.&nbsp;</strong>Visible reminders can keep your agreements top of mind for your group. Some ideas include displaying them in your offices, hanging posters in conference rooms, and adding the agreements to meeting slides.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong><em>Note:&nbsp;</em></strong>If a colleague points out your use of non-inclusive language, accept the feedback with gratitude and express willingness to change. In this situation, it’s best to offer a sincere apology, learn from the mistake, and do better.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Take a leap of faith.&nbsp;</strong>Using the correct gender and pronouns is as essential to people as using their correct names. Extending this courtesy shows kindness and respect that builds bridges and trust.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Inclusive language is a lifelong practice, not a destination.&nbsp;</strong>Language and meaning constantly evolve. Keep learning, pay attention to the language people use to describe themselves, and let that guide you. If you mess up, apologize, move on, and do better the next time.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Language evolves.</strong>&nbsp;Inclusive language is different today than it was a decade ago. Like everything else, language is constantly changing. So, remember the tips you learned in this lesson and continue learning. Be mindful of updates—and do your part to respect various racial and ethnic groups with their chosen terminology.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Assistive devices are enabling and have a positive impact.&nbsp;</strong>The way we describe them should reflect that. Think of assistive options such as mobility aids, screen readers, and closed captions as helpful tools. So instead of “he is wheelchair-<em>bound</em>” or<em>&nbsp;</em>“<em>confined</em>&nbsp;to a wheelchair,”<em>&nbsp;</em>simply say “he&nbsp;<em>uses</em>&nbsp;a wheelchair.” Rather than “they&nbsp;<em>have to</em>&nbsp;have a service animal,” consider, “they&nbsp;<em>use</em>&nbsp;a service animal.”</li></ul><p></p><p><ul><li><strong><em>Tip:&nbsp;</em>Look at the work from a different perspective.</strong>&nbsp;When crafting content for an online audience, reread the final draft and ask yourself:&nbsp;<em>“Does anything I have written have the potential to be a barrier or exclude someone?”&nbsp;</em>If the answer is yes, find a more inclusive way to convey the idea before publishing your work.</li></ul></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-2-inclusive-communication-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong><br></p><ul><li><strong>Understand </strong>and develop cultural competence</li><li>Have the <strong>capability </strong>to present information across cultures</li><li><strong>Know-how </strong>to move through the stages of cultural sensitivity</li><li><strong>Manage </strong>multicultural teams</li><li><strong>Avoid</strong> cultural appropriation</li><li><strong>Accommodate </strong>religion, spirituality and beliefs in the workplace</li><li><strong>Enable </strong>discussions involving hot-buttons issues</li></ul><br><br><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-3-culture-competence-learning-outcome';
