UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><strong>Summary</strong></p><p dir="ltr"></p><ul><li>Make a long-term commitment. Building a respectful workplace doesn’t happen overnight. More than a simple project or quarterly goal, it requires a long-term, ongoing commitment. It means staying firm through continuous monitoring, re-evaluation, and training.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Unsure if compensation differences are justified? Work with your human resources team or legal counsel to determine whether differences in pay are appropriately justified.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>People aren’t required to disclose disabilities. Not all disabilities are obvious. Unless someone needs a reasonable accommodation to do their job, no employee or applicant is required to disclose a disability.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Is it illegal discrimination? How can you be sure if you’re experiencing illegal discrimination? If you suspect that decisions are based on anything other than your work—or if your religious, pregnancy, or disability needs aren’t being reasonably accommodated—you may be a victim of discrimination. Refer back to those legal requirements and never hesitate to speak up if something doesn’t seem right.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Discrimination can happen in all areas of employment. A person might be treated unfairly based on any one, or several, of the above factors. Mistreatment can happen in all employment areas—such as when getting access to benefits, training, or mentorship opportunities—as well as during the hiring process, salary negotiations, job assignments, evaluations, disciplinary actions, and termination decisions.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Be mindful of the impact. “I didn’t mean anything by it,” is not a valid excuse for offensive or discriminatory behavior. Harassment and discrimination are determined by the impact, not the intent, of the words or behavior.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><ul><li>Is it sexual harassment? Are you experiencing an uncomfortable situation and unsure if it’s sexual harassment? Sometimes, it’s not always clear-cut, so do this self-check: If a person’s ongoing jokes, propositions, sexual advances, comments, touches, or glances are making you feel intimidated or uncomfortable, it may be sexual harassment. If you’re ever unsure, don’t hesitate to contact your human resources team and let them know what’s happening.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>When in doubt—don’t. If you’re unsure if a behavior or comment is appropriate for work, then it probably isn’t. A little self-monitoring can go a long way toward contributing to a safe and comfortable work environment.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Each situation is unique. Keep in mind that every instance of sexual harassment is unique. Only you can decide what feels right and how far to take the complaint. Take as many of the steps you feel comfortable taking, but do your best not to ignore the problem. Remember, the only way to stop the abuse is to speak out.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Trust your gut. If you see or hear something that doesn’t feel right to you, then it probably isn’t. Don’t second-guess yourself or dismiss your intuition. Approach the person who you believe was targeted by sexual harassment and ask them if they were OK with the situation or if they need help.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Prevention must be ongoing. Prevention starts with you and the example you set for others—and it must be an ongoing process. Even with the right policies and practices in place, you can still run into issues if you don’t maintain that culture of respect. Training sessions should be held regularly. Communication should be ongoing. And prevention should be embedded into the company culture.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li>Keep reports of sexual harassment on a “need-to-know” basis. Keep the complaint as confidential as possible. Do not talk about the specifics of the complaint with other employees who are not involved in the situation.</li></ul><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-7-anti-harassment-and-discrimination-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong></p><ul><li>Have the&nbsp;<strong>capability</strong>&nbsp;to build a talent management strategy</li><li><strong>Understand</strong>&nbsp;how to attract and source top talent</li><li><strong>Know-how&nbsp;</strong>to attract, retain, develop employees talent</li><li><strong>Implement</strong>&nbsp;a process for employee transitioning to growth and new roles</li><li><strong>Capable </strong>of implementing strategies for retaining talent and minimizing turnover</li></ul><br><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-5-talent-management-learning-outcome';
