UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><strong>Summary</strong></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><span><strong>Check your tangible brand elements against your intangible brand.</strong> Is there a disconnect, or do they\r\nmatch? For example, a playful tween fashion brand might choose bright logo elements and avoid dour\r\ncolors, while a federally insured financial institution might consider a formal logo and colors.</span></li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Ask a friend for feedback.</strong> Whether you’re struggling to identify traits that fit or 100% confident in your\r\nchoices—it’s still worth getting a second opinion. Ask: “What’s your experience of the brand?” or, “What\r\nadjectives would you use to describe us?” If your answers are dramatically different from theirs, revisit your\r\nself-assessment.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Don’t forget about white space.</strong> As you build your brand visual design, remember to leave room for\r\nthose elements to breathe, known as “white space.”</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Feeling stuck? </strong>Try audience personas. A persona is an imagined character that represents your ideal\r\nbuyer. As you consider the audience’s wants and needs, personas humanize your customer to help you\r\nunderstand them on a deeper level.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Remember your audience is the target. </strong>It’s a common mistake to insert your own feelings and ideas into\r\nthe process. Instead, use the brand position as a GPS and test all messaging against that coordinate.\r\nFocus on your audience\'s feelings and ideas to make sure your message lands just where you want it to.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Look at examples from other brands. </strong>Review your favorite brands’ stories for inspiration, and research\r\ncompetitors to determine how best to position yourself.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Gather input and create alignment. </strong>Company leaders and employees must be in alignment for\r\nrebranding to work. Gather perspectives and get buy-in from key stakeholders before moving forward.\r\nCreate a Plan to Announce\r\nChanges\r\nPrepare a Style Guide and Asset\r\nKit\r\nYou might also hire a brand consultant or market research firm for a professional, data-driven opinion.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-2-brand-identity-and-strategy-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong></p><p dir="ltr"></p><ul><li><strong>Understand</strong>&nbsp;content marketing and why you need it for your business</li><li>Have the&nbsp;<strong>capability</strong>&nbsp;to choose a suitable content distribution channel for your product or service</li><li><strong>Know-how&nbsp;</strong>to create content for your target audience</li><li><strong>Know-how&nbsp;</strong>to create your voice and tone in content marketing</li><li><strong>Develop</strong> your content own strategy</li><li><strong>Use</strong> marketing funnel tools to increase your buying customers</li><li><strong>Know-how </strong>to create engaging content</li><li><strong>Start </strong>your business blog</li></ul><br><br><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-4-content-marketing-learning-outcome';
