UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<video controls="true"><source src="https://goalvow.com/upskilling/pluginfile.php/976/mod_label/intro/12_Sales%20Leadership%20and%20Management.mp4?time=1709805373915">https://goalvow.com/upskilling/pluginfile.php/976/mod_label/intro/12_Sales%20Leadership%20and%20Management.mp4?time=1709805373915</video>&nbsp;<br></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-2-sales-leadership-and-management-lesson-12-the-basics-of-creating-a-sales-forecast';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><b>Summary</b></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong>Ask for honest feedback.&nbsp;</strong>Especially if this is your first leadership role, be open to honest feedback from your team and management colleagues. Honest feedback can be uncomfortable in the short term—but it will help you improve in the long run.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Hold yourself accountable.</strong>&nbsp;Ultimately, your actions will make or break your team’s success. So, be sure you’re giving your team the best chance to excel. To measure your effectiveness, meet with sales reps individually and ask what’s working and what’s not. Or, ask a supervisor or mentor for an honest assessment of your performance.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Is one methodology enough for your team?&nbsp;</strong>Probably not. No single strategy works in every situation. As your company grows and business needs evolve, so will the methods you use to close sales. What worked in one stage of your company’s growth may fall flat in another. So, arm your team with several effective methodologies and adapt your approach when needed.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Which department owns sales enablement?&nbsp;</strong>Confusion sometimes arises when determining which department is responsible for sales enablement. If sales enablement sounds like a marketing responsibility to you, you’re partially correct. It’s actually a joint effort between the sales and marketing teams. Typically, sales communicates its needs to marketing, which then creates resources for reps to use during the selling process.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Create a playbook for each stage of your process.</strong>&nbsp;With your sales process in place, you can take your team’s efforts to the next level by creating a playbook for each stage. Include an overview of each stage, its purpose, the exit criteria, and a step-by-step guide for successfully moving potential customers and clients forward in the process.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Be careful not to over-automate.</strong>&nbsp;You know that saying,<em>&nbsp;“Too much of a good thing”?</em>&nbsp;If you automate every aspect of your sales process, your buyer’s experience will feel robotic. Focus on those areas that cost your team valuable time when they could be talking to potential customers instead.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Don’t force people to sell in ways that feel uncomfortable.</strong>&nbsp;Stretching your salespeople will allow them to learn new skills, but that shouldn’t extend to trying to turn your salespeople into hybrid sellers. Let your hunters and farmers grow organically within their preferred approach to selling.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Talk to your team directly.</strong>&nbsp;What’s working well? What isn’t? Solicit input to choose and maintain the roles and structure that will allow your team to shine.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Collaboration is key.&nbsp;</strong>While it’s a sales manager’s responsibility to oversee team performance, improvements only happen when everyone participates. What are some ways you can make it fun to engage? Be creative and take chances.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Set goals as a team.</strong>&nbsp;Before carving your quotas in stone, consider looping your sales reps into the process. They can offer additional insights on what’s realistic and what truly motivates them. Also, sales reps who have buy-in will be more likely to hold themselves accountable.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Design a battle card template.&nbsp;</strong>Templates give battle cards a consistent look and feel and make creating new ones a snap. The consistency a template provides also helps sales reps easily find information since they know where to look and what to expect on each card.</li></ul><p><ul><li><strong>How far into the future should you forecast?&nbsp;</strong>The further you forecast into the future, the less accurate your predictions will be. A good, general rule is to forecast monthly for 12 months into the future. Then, forecast annually for an additional three to five years. Also, remember that your forecast isn’t set in stone. Adjust it as new information and data become available.</li></ul></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-2-sales-leadership-and-management-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong>Develop</strong> your proposal</li><li><strong>Know-how </strong>to prepare for your a sales presentation</li><li><strong>Tailor </strong>your presentation to an audience</li><li><strong>Make </strong>the most of slide decks in sales presentation</li><li><strong>Understand </strong>the winning sales techniques</li><li><strong>Create </strong>your sales narrative</li><li><strong>Understand </strong>the role of storytelling in sales</li><li><strong>Translate </strong>features into benefits</li><li><strong>Give </strong>an effective product demonstration</li></ul><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-4-presenting-your-solution-learning-outcome';
