UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><b>Summary</b></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong>Create and use proposal templates.&nbsp;</strong>They make customization easy and can save you time and effort when putting together your next document. Consider saving drafts of your proposals to use as templates for future projects.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Don’t read directly from your notes.&nbsp;</strong>Aim to engage your audience in conversation. Use your notes and visual aids as guides to help you keep your audience’s attention.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Get creative!&nbsp;</strong>Like Grace, you aren’t bound to a presentation template. As long as you’re keeping your audience and their expectations in mind, you can push the boundaries of traditional presentations. Doing so can make you stand out even more.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Email a copy of your slide deck after the presentation.&nbsp;</strong>This gives you an opportunity to follow up with the prospect and remind them of your solution’s selling points.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Communicate with certainty.&nbsp;</strong>Avoid phrases that undermine your authority, such as,&nbsp;<em>“I believe”</em>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<em>“I think.”</em>&nbsp;Instead, communicate with confidence and certainty. For example, instead of saying,&nbsp;<em>“I believe that our solution is a good fit for you because … ”</em>&nbsp;try,&nbsp;<em>“</em><em>Our solution will … ”&nbsp;</em></li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong style="">Use your imagination.&nbsp;</strong>Think about your own life. What kind of adventure would you like to go on with your product? What’s the desired outcome you’d hope for at the end of the transformation?&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Study your favorite stand-up comedian.&nbsp;</strong>Stand-up comedy is chock full of brilliantly told stories. Analyze and dissect the patterns. How do comedians construct and deliver points in ways that bring joy and satisfaction to the audience?</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Learn as much as you can about prospective customers upfront.&nbsp;</strong>The more you know about their situation and needs, the easier it will be to identify relevant benefits.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>What is the goal of persuasion?&nbsp;</strong>Ask yourself this question to clarify intention before meeting a prospect. Are you trying to persuade someone to make the sale, or are you persuading them that your product is the right fit—if that is indeed the case? This subtle difference can help you distinguish between persuasion and manipulation.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>End your product demonstration with a call to action.&nbsp;</strong>Once you’ve successfully demonstrated your product’s value in the demo, ask the prospect to take the next step in the sales process. See if they’ll sign up for a subscription, agree to a product purchase—or introduce you to the decision-maker who can sign on the dotted line.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p><br></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-4-presenting-your-solution-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module you will be able to:</strong></p><p dir="ltr"></p><ul><li><strong></strong><strong>Understand</strong> the Fundamentals of Prospecting</li><li><strong>Apply</strong> Effective Prospecting Techniques</li><li><strong></strong><strong>Analyze and Differentiate</strong> from Competitors</li><li><strong></strong><strong>Master</strong> Cold and Warm Calling</li><li><strong>Leverage</strong> Social Selling for Prospecting<br></li></ul><br><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-8-prospecting-learning-outcome';
