UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><strong>Summary</strong></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong>Stay on good terms.&nbsp;</strong>If you decide that it’s time to find a new job, avoid burning bridges on your way out. Give appropriate notice. Have a plan in place. And do everything you can to make the transition smooth for your former boss and team. They may be important contacts to have in your network for landing the position that is right for you.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Allocate space on your resume by level of importance.&nbsp;</strong>For example, allocate more space to describe your most recent job experience and less space to describe a less relevant internship. Pay attention to how much visual space each section of your resume consumes.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Talk about what you can offer the job—instead of what the job can offer you.&nbsp;</strong>Sure, employers like to know why the job appeals to you or why you’re passionate about your work—but that shouldn’t take over your entire cover letter. Don’t spend too much time on your cover letter gushing about why the job is ideal for you. Remember, your goal is to communicate why you’d be ideal for the job.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Send a thank-you email within 48 hours after the interview.&nbsp;</strong>A thank-you note doesn’t have to be long or complicated. You might simply tell the interviewer(s) that you enjoyed meeting with them—and note a few specific details of the conversation or process that excited you, or reinforced why you believe you’d be a good fit for the position.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Do you have any questions you’d like to ask me?&nbsp;</strong>If an interviewer asks you this question, then your answer should always be,&nbsp;<em>“Yes.”</em>&nbsp;Come prepared with a few thoughtful and tailored questions that show you’ve done your research on the company and care about making sure the job is the right fit.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><ul><li><strong>What’s your ideal workday?&nbsp;</strong>When deciding if remote work is right for you, think about an ideal day at the office. Do you prefer being left to your own devices with minimal distractions? Or, do you enjoy spending time with coworkers? If you prefer being alone, then a remote job might be an ideal fit for you.</li></ul><p><ul><li><strong>Tailor your resume and cover letter to the position.&nbsp;</strong>Never submit a generic resume to multiple job openings. Every application should be customized and specific to the job description and qualifications.</li></ul></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-3-finding-a-new-job-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong></p><p dir="ltr"></p><ul><li><strong>Understand </strong>the role of a mentor in your career development and how do find one</li><li><strong>Know-how </strong>to be a model mentee</li><li><strong>Guide </strong>others as a mentor</li><li><strong>Overcome </strong>common mentoring challenges</li></ul></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-6-mentoring-in-the-workplace-learning-outcome';
