UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<video controls="true"><source src="https://goalvow.com/upskilling/pluginfile.php/988/mod_label/intro/8_Communicating%20in%20Difficult%20Situations.mp4?time=1709999214001">https://goalvow.com/upskilling/pluginfile.php/988/mod_label/intro/8_Communicating%20in%20Difficult%20Situations.mp4?time=1709999214001</video>&nbsp;<br></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-8-communicating-in-difficult-situations-lesson-8-how-to-have-a-difficult-conversation';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><strong>Summary</strong></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong>Report bullying, harassment, or illegal behavior.&nbsp;</strong>You do not need to handle challenges which involve bullying, harassment, or illegal behavior on your own. Follow company protocol for reporting these behaviors and seeking support from your supervisor or human resources.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Ask what they prefer.</strong>&nbsp;If you’re unsure what communication style the other person prefers, just ask them directly. For example, you might ask, “What’s your preferred communication style?” Or, “Is there anything I could change or do differently to communicate more effectively?” They’ll appreciate the effort, and you won’t have to guess what works best for them.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Keep it confidential.&nbsp;</strong>Don’t gossip or discuss issues you’re having with a difficult coworker publicly. Talk directly to your coworker. Keep your complaints between the two of you. The only exception is when dealing with a workplace bully. Document abuse and discuss it with an appropriate supervisor or human resources professional.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Don’t leapfrog your boss.</strong>&nbsp;Going over your boss’s head will likely damage your relationship with your boss more than it will produce helpful results. Use the strategies in this lesson to see what changes you can make to improve your relationship, or confront your boss directly.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Imagine what you would do.</strong>&nbsp;Imagine how you’d approach the issue if your boss weren’t there. Compare your thoughts to your boss’s response. Even if your hypothetical approach is wrong, this exercise is good practice for your critical-thinking and problem-solving skills.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Check your employee handbook.&nbsp;</strong>Try to find your own answers by checking your employee handbook, or reviewing workplace policies, before going to HR.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Model others’ behavior.</strong>&nbsp;Pay attention to how a successful manager or mentor manages conflict and approaches confrontation. Consider the language that the person uses, their demeanor, and how they structure the conversation. Then model similar behaviors and techniques the next time you need to address a problem.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><ul><li><strong>Acknowledge your shortcomings.</strong>&nbsp;People are more willing to be vulnerable after you’ve expressed vulnerability first. You can be vulnerable by acknowledging the role you played in a problem. Openly admit what you could have improved and what feelings may have driven your behavior. When you go first, the other person might be more willing to discuss difficult topics and work through them together. Show that you\'re willing to admit mistakes.&nbsp;</li></ul></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-8-communicating-in-difficult-situations-module-summary';
