UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><strong>Summary</strong></p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><ul><li><strong>Boil it down to one sentence.&nbsp;</strong>Try to combine your insights and compress your objective into a single sentence. It will be easier to share—and to remember while developing your presentation.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Look for gaps.&nbsp;</strong>Practice your presentation on someone who’s not familiar with the topic. Do they understand what you’re saying? Can they clearly follow your presentation structure? Ask targeted questions after your practice session to identify gaps where the audience may get lost or confused.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Assign one topic per visual aid.</strong>&nbsp;Focus each visual aid on communicating just one main idea or topic. Review your presentation outline if you’re having trouble discerning your presentation’s main ideas.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><ul><li><strong>Research design tools.</strong>&nbsp;There are plenty of free and paid design tools available to use. From Canva, Google Slides, Keynote, and Microsoft PowerPoint for slide deck design—to sites like Pexels and Librestock for stock photography—a little online research may save you time and give you some design inspiration.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Make a list.</strong>&nbsp;It can be a fine line between a presentation that’s supported by data versus one overtaken by data. Don’t make the mistake of falling into the latter! Make a list of the data points that are critical for the audience to remember after your presentation is over. Limit your list to three and focus on communicating just those points. &nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><p></p><ul><li><strong>Record yourself.&nbsp;</strong>Record a video of your practice presentation on your phone, laptop, or another device. Watch the recording afterward to look for areas where you can improve your presentation!&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Write down your fears.</strong>&nbsp;Ignoring your fears can give them more power over you. Write a list of what makes you nervous about your presentation. Get as specific as possible. Admitting your fears can help you come up with strategies to manage them. It can also help you accept and move past them.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Don’t let one audience member monopolize your time.&nbsp;</strong>If one person is asking all of the questions, the rest of the audience may grow bored or restless. Thank the overenthusiastic audience member for their question, and then turn to the rest of the audience and ask if anyone else would like to ask you something.</li></ul><p><ul><li><strong>Practice—then practice again.</strong>&nbsp;One of the best ways to identify opportunities to improve your presentation is to rehearse it. Whether rehearsing in front of the mirror, recording yourself on video, or arranging a test audience of close friends, conducting a thorough practice run is the best way to spot holes or hiccups in your presentation.&nbsp;</li></ul></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-5-presentations-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong></p><p dir="ltr"></p><ul><li><strong>Improve </strong>your verbal communication skills</li><li><strong>Start </strong>a conversation</li><li><strong>Implement&nbsp;</strong>strategies for effective listening</li><li><strong>Ask </strong>closed vs. open questions</li><li><strong>Rectify and Clarify </strong>communication mistakes</li><li><strong>End </strong>a conversation positively</li><li><strong>Become </strong>an expert verbal communicator</li></ul><br><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-3-verbal-communication-learning-outcome';
