UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p><strong>Summary</strong></p><p></p><ul><li><strong>Write down your purpose.&nbsp;</strong>Before you write your next message, take a moment to ask yourself:&nbsp;<em>“What is my number one goal for communicating this message?”&nbsp;</em>After you answer that question, write your purpose down somewhere so that it’s easy to see.</li></ul><p></p><p>As you write your message, challenge yourself to keep looking back at that purpose. Are you staying on track? Keep your goal in mind, and you’ll then be more likely to meet it.&nbsp;</p><ul><li><strong>Does the medium fit the message?&nbsp;</strong>Before you seal the envelope, print the report, or press “enter” on your keyboard, think it through. Remember, the medium will set the tone of your message. Choose the wrong one, and you could dilute your communication. Consider&nbsp;<strong>urgency</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>formality</strong>, and&nbsp;<strong>length</strong>, and ask yourself: Does this medium work? &nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Your tone can change.&nbsp;</strong>Keep in mind that as your relationships change, so can your tone. At the start of most business communications, you’ll want to use a professional tone as a means of showing respect. If you note that the other person is moving toward a more informal style, you can mirror their language.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Read the first and last sentence.&nbsp;</strong>Is your structure following the broad-narrow-broad approach? Try this trick to make sure: Read only the first and last sentences of each paragraph. Do all your transitions connect and flow together? Does everything make sense? If not, see if you can adjust what you’re saying so that your points logically link together.</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Practice, practice, practice.&nbsp;</strong>One of the best ways to improve your spelling, grammar, and punctuation is to recognize your weaknesses and stay committed to fixing them. The more you practice and develop your writing, the more natural these skills will become.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><ul><li><strong>Know your weaknesses.&nbsp;</strong>We all have our weaknesses. We might confuse&nbsp;<em>“affect”&nbsp;</em>and&nbsp;<em>“effect,”&nbsp;</em>forget to close quotation marks, or use incomplete comparisons. What are your common writing&nbsp;<em>faux pas?&nbsp;</em>The next time you get feedback on your writing, note your most common problems and keep these weaknesses in mind. That way, you’ll know what to look out for when editing and proofreading your work in the future.</li></ul><p><ul><li><strong>Save time with a process.&nbsp;</strong>The next time you need to write something, think about what you need to say and how you should say it before you start. It’ll save your time when you actually start writing.</li></ul></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-7-writing-well-module-summary';
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"></p><p dir="ltr"><strong>After completing this module, you will be able to:</strong></p><p dir="ltr"></p><ul><li><strong>Understand</strong>&nbsp;what is crisis and how to manage it</li><li><strong>Know</strong>&nbsp;and<span> <span style="">differentiate between different types of business crisis</span></span></li><li>Have the <strong>capability</strong> to prevent and prepare for a crisis</li><li><strong>Know-how&nbsp;</strong>to respond to a crisis</li><li><strong>Implement</strong>&nbsp;a recovery plan after a crisis</li></ul><br><p></p></div>' WHERE slug = 'module-4-crisis-management-learning-outcome';
